abstract = {This chapter gives an overview of digital elevation model (DEM) data sources, their processing requirements, their advantages, disadvantages, and their applications. There are three sources of DEM data: (1) Ground survey techniques: the accurate surveying of point locations. The chapter discusses the traditional and high-tech ground survey techniques. (2) Existing topographic maps: The derivation of contours, streams, lakes, and elevation points from hardcopy topographic maps. It focuses on digitizing and semi-automatic scanning to convert raster images of topographic maps into vectors. (3) Remote sensing: The interpretation of image data acquired from airborne or satellite platforms. Here particular attention is paid to: (i) Photogrammetric/stereo methods; (ii) Laser; and (iii) Radar. The chapter discusses each of these sources in turn and the most common DEM products derived from them. Data sources and processing methods for generating DEMs have developed rapidly over the last few decades — from ground surveying to passive methods of remote sensing, and more recently to the emergence of active sensors, such as LiDAR and RADAR. Higher levels of accuracy, more detail, and a larger, and more rapid, areal coverage, but at lower cost, has been a natural consequence of these new technologies.},
